[[File:Gewickeltes Baby Regiment-der-jungen-Kinder.jpg|thumb|Swaddled baby is given to the nurse, 1549, frontpage of Bartholomäus Metlinger's ''Regiment der jungen Kinder''.]] '''Bartholomäus Metlinger''' (born in [[Augsburg]] - died c.1491) was a German physician of the late [[Middle Ages]].<ref>Scheibenreiter, page 28.</ref>
Metlinger graduated in 1470 at the [[University of Bologna]]. He was city physician in [[Nördlingen]] from 1476 to 1483, when he took the same position in [[Augsburg]], probably succeeding his late father Peter Metlinger.
His most famous work ''Kinderbüchlein'' ("Little Book on Children") was published on 7 December 1473, being retitled on later editions as ''Ein Regiment der jungen Kinder'' (A Guide on Young Children).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.europeana.eu/resolve/record/03486/BibliographicResource_1000128570713|title=Ein Regiment der jungen Kinder|author=Metlinger, Bartholomäus |accessdate=2014-09-25 |publisher=Europeana}}</ref> It was the first German-language work on [[Pediatrics]]. In it, Metlinger deals with the care of infants and small children up to the age of seven. The book describes several childhood diseases and their treatments, besides providing educational advice. It also contains one of the first known written definitions of a [[pacifier]].
