Central Atlas Tamazight uses a bipartate negative construction (e.g. /uriffiɣ ʃa/ 'he didn't go out') which apparently was modeled after proximate [[Arabic language|Arabic]] varieties, in a common development known as [[Jespersen's Cycle]].<ref>[http://people.pwf.cam.ac.uk/cbl23/ContactRevised170708.pdf Contact-induced grammatical change: towards an explicit account]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (PDF), p. 2.</ref> This is a phenomenon where a postverbal item is reanalyzed as being an element of a discontinuous negation marker composed of it and the preverbal negation marker.<ref name="jespersen">[http://people.pwf.cam.ac.uk/cbl23/revisedjesaraber.pdf Jespersen's Cycle in Arabic and Berber]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (PDF), p. 1.</ref> It is present in multiple Berber varieties, and is argued to have originated in neighboring Arabic and been adopted by contact.<ref name="jespersen" />

Standard negation is accompanied by a negative indefinite pronoun, ''walu''.<ref>[http://www.linguistics.berkeley.edu/~syntax-circle/syntax-group/spr08/miestamo.pdf Negation – An Overview of Typological Research] (PDF), pp. 13-14.</ref>

{| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;"
|+ Imperative conjugation of {{IPA|/rwl/}} 'run' in 2nd person<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971a|p=227}}</ref>
! colspan="2" | !! AA !! AS
