| colspan="2" | {{IPA|/rwlnt/}}
|}

Tamazight has a [[null copula]].<ref name="inalco_syntax" /> The words {{IPA|/ɡ/}} {{IPA|/iʒ/}} 'to be, to do' may function as a copula in Ayt Ayache and Ayt Seghrouchen respectively, especially in structures preceded by /aj/ 'who, which, what'.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971a|p=298}}</ref>

Many Arabic loans have been integrated into the Tamazight verb lexicon. They adhere fully to patterns of native stems, and may even undergo ablaut.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971b|p=153}}</ref>

'''Ablaut'''

In Ayt Ayache, [[ablaut]] occurs only in affirmative and/or negative past (in applicable verb classes). Types of ablaut include Ø:i/a,  Ø:i, and a:u, which may be accompanied by [[Metathesis (linguistics)|metathesis]].<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971b|pp=161–166}}</ref> In Ayt Seghrouchen types of ablaut include Ø:i (in negative), i/a, i/u, a-u, and a-i.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971b|pp=218–219}}</ref>

== Adjectives ==

Adjectives come after the noun the modify, and inflect for number and gender:<ref>[http://wals.info/languoid/lect/wals_code_bma WALS - Beber (Middle Atlas)]</ref><ref name="s23">{{Harvcoltxt|Sadiqi|1986|p=23}}</ref>
<!-- examples from Sadiqi: -->
: /argaz amʕdur/ 'the foolish man' (lit. 'man foolish')
: /tamtˤot tamʕdurt/ 'the foolish woman' <!-- /o/ can't be phonemic! -->
: /irgzen imʕdar/ 'the foolish men'
: /tajtʃin timʕdar/ 'the foolish women'

Adjectives may also occur alone, in which case they become an NP.<ref name="s23" />

Practically all adjectives also have a verbal form used for predicative purposes, which behaves just like a normal verb:<ref name="s23" />
: /i-mmuʕdr urgaz/ 'the man is foolish' (lit. '3ps-foolish man')
: /argaz i-mmuʕdr-n/ 'the foolish man' [using a non-finite verb]

As such, adjectives may be classed as a subset of verbs which also have other non-verbal features.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Sadiqi|1986|p=24}}</ref> However Penchoen (1973:21) argues that they are actually nouns.

== Particles ==

'''Prepositions'''

Prepositions include {{IPA|/xf/}} ('on'), {{IPA|/qbl/}} ('before'), {{IPA|/ɣɾ/}} ('to'), and {{IPA|/ɡ/}} ('until'). These may take pronominal suffixes (see Pronouns).

Some prepositions require the following noun to be in the construct state, while others do not.

