{{IPA|/n/}} encliticizes onto the following word (which is put into construct state), and assimilates to some initial consonants: it becomes {{IPA|/l/}} before a noun with initial {{IPA|/l/}}, {{IPA|/w/}} before initial {{IPA|/a/}}, and {{IPA|/j/}} before initial {{IPA|/i/}} (note that this creates geminates rather than doubled phonemes, e.g. {{IPA|/ʃa lːħlib/}} 'some milk').<ref name="ReferenceC">{{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971b|pp=124–125}}</ref> Nouns with initial {{IPA|/a/}} normally drop in when following {{IPA|/ʃa/}} 'some of', e.g. {{IPA|/ʃa wksum/}} (< |{{IPA|ʃa n aksum}}|) 'some meat', but some don't, following the normal rules of construct state, e.g. {{IPA|/ʃa wːataj/}} (< |{{IPA|ʃa n ataj}}|) 'some tea'.<ref name="ReferenceC"/>

'''Conjunctions'''

The conjunction {{IPA|/d/}} 'and' requires construct state, and also assimilates to a following {{IPA|/t/}}, e.g. {{IPA|/aɣjul tːfunast/}} 'the donkey and the cow'.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971b|p=125}}</ref>

Other conjunctions include:
