Cardinal numbers precede the modified noun, connected by the preposition {{IPA|/n/}} (optional for the number 1).<ref>C.f. {{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971b|pp=23–25, 27}}</ref>

The procliticization-triggered phonological change of {{IPA|/n/}} may cause {{IPA|/jun/}} / {{IPA|/jut/}} and {{IPA|/sin/}} to become proclitics {{IPA|/ju-/}}, {{IPA|/si-/}}, e.g. {{IPA|/julːʕil/}} ('one boy'), {{IPA|/jutːɾbatː ~ jut ntɾbatː/}} ('one girl'), {{IPA|/siwːaɾːjalː/}} ('two rials').<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971b|pp=23–24}}</ref>

When referring to money, {{IPA|/qːlː/}} ('minus') and {{IPA|/ɣiɾ/}} ('except') may be used, for example: {{IPA|/mjːa qːlː/}} / {{IPA|/ɣiɾ ʕʃɾˠa/}} ('90 [rials]'), {{IPA|/mitajn qːlː ʕʃɾin/}} ('180 [rials]'), {{IPA|/mitajn ɣiɾ xmsa/}} ('195 [rials]').<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971b|p=20}}</ref>

Nouns following numerals require construct state.

'''Ordinal numerals'''

The word for 'the first' is unique in that it is not derived from a cardinal stem and it inflects for number:
{| class="wikitable"
|-
! 'the first'
! singular
! plural
|-
! m
| {{IPA|/amzwaɾu/}}
| {{IPA|/imzwura/}}
|-
! f
| {{IPA|/tamzwaɾutː/}}
| {{IPA|/timzwura/}}
|}

From 'the second' on, ordinals are formed by prefixing {{IPA|/wisː-/}} in the masculine and {{IPA|/tisː-/}} in the feminine (using the native Berber forms of 2 and 3).

'''Fractions'''

There are unique words which may be used for some fractions, although male ordinals can be used for 1/4 on.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971b|pp=31–32}}</ref>

