== Syntax ==
Word order is usually Verb + Subject [in construct state] but sometimes is Subject [in free state] + Verb, e.g. ({{IPA|/ifːɣ umaziɣ/}} vs. {{IPA|/amaziɣ ifːɣ/}} 'the Berber went out').<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abdel-Massih|1971b|p=295}}</ref> Tamazight exhibits [[pro-drop]] behavior.
<ref>[http://www.hum2.leidenuniv.nl/pdf/lucl/sole/console12/console12-stoyanova.pdf The typology of multiple wh-questions and language variation] (PDF), p. 172.</ref>

===Questions===

wh- questions are always [[cleft sentence|cleft]]s, and multiple wh-questions are not found.<ref name="Stoyanova 2008 105">{{Harvcoltxt|Stoyanova|2008|p=105}}</ref> This means that Tamazight cannot grammatically express an equivalent to the English "who saw what?".
<ref>[http://www.hum2.leidenuniv.nl/pdf/lucl/sole/console12/console12-stoyanova.pdf The typology of multiple wh-questions and language variation] (PDF), pp. 174-175.</ref>

Tamazight's clefting, relativisation, and wh-interrogation cause what is called "anti-agreement effects", similarly to [[Shilha language|Shilha]].<ref name="Stoyanova 2008 105"/> This is when the verb doesn't agree with or agrees in a special way with wh-words.<ref>[http://web.mit.edu/norvin/www/papers/WampanoagConjunct.pdf The Syntax of the Conjunct and Independent Orders in Wampanoag] (PDF), p. 18.</ref> In Berber, the feminine singular prefix {{IPA|/t-/}} disappears when the subject is a wh- phrase, but only for [[affirmative (linguistics)|affirmative]] verbs.<ref>[http://web.mit.edu/norvin/www/papers/WampanoagConjunct.pdf The Syntac of the Conjunct and Independent Orders in Wampanoag] (PDF), p. 19.</ref>

